The proposed architecture transitions the existing monolithic application into a microservices-based platform deployed on Amazon EKS. This improves scalability, fault isolation, and deployment agility.
A multi-account AWS structure is implemented using AWS Organizations to separate production, development, security, and shared services. This enhances governance and aligns with PCI-DSS compliance requirements.
High availability is ensured by deploying the EKS cluster across multiple availability zones and configuring Amazon RDS in Multi-AZ mode with read replicas for scaling read operations.
To eliminate downtime during deployments, a blue-green deployment strategy is implemented using CI/CD pipelines integrated with Kubernetes rolling updates.
Disaster recovery is addressed through a multi-region architecture with active-passive failover using Route 53. Database replication across regions ensures minimal data loss.
Centralized logging and monitoring are implemented using CloudWatch, CloudTrail, and log aggregation into a shared services account, enabling efficient incident response and auditing.
Secrets are securely managed using AWS Secrets Manager and integrated with EKS using IAM roles for service accounts, ensuring no hardcoded credentials.
Cost optimization is achieved using auto-scaling, reserved instances, and efficient resource allocation.
